      Endless shrimp
   =20
 =20

We talked yesterday about the corporate finance angle on Red Lobster=E2=80=
=99s Ultimate Endless Shrimp promotion, but at Slate, Luke Winkie addresses=
 the labor-relations and nutritional angles:

=E2=80=9CI had a guy come in with his family. It was a family of five. And =
he did 16 rounds of shrimp scampi,=E2=80=9D said James Berke, a 23-year-old=
 in New Jersey, who until very recently worked at a Red Lobster. =E2=80=9CH=
e was there for over two hours on a busy Friday night. They had one of my b=
iggest tables. I just had to watch this man eat plates upon plates of the s=
campi, which isn=E2=80=99t even served over pasta. It=E2=80=99s shrimp in a=
 garlic-wine butter. It was so gross.=E2=80=9D ...
Berke=E2=80=99s experience serving a man who put away 16 servings over the =
course of two hours was actually mild compared with some of the other stori=
es I=E2=80=99ve heard. Josie, 19, who also asked to be anonymous, worked at=
 a (now-shuttered) Kansas City Red Lobster, where she watched a solo diner =
take down 30 orders of fried shrimp within four hours. According to the nut=
ritional information on Red Lobster=E2=80=99s website, that=E2=80=99s somet=
hing like 14,000 calories.
=E2=80=9CHe was a skinny guy too,=E2=80=9D Josie said. =E2=80=9CI was like,=
 Where is it all going?=E2=80=9D
But the top thing employees will not miss about Red Lobster are the argumen=
ts and confrontations they=E2=80=99d frequently endure when informing custo=
mers about the rules that come buoyed to the Endless Shrimp deal. For insta=
nce, guests cannot request a box to take their Endless Shrimp home, nor can=
 they share their servings with the rest of the table. (In other words, onl=
y one phantasmagoric shrimp binge per person.)
=E2=80=9CYou had groups coming in expecting to feed their whole family with=
 one order of endless shrimp,=E2=80=9D Josie said. =E2=80=9CI would get scr=
eamed at.=E2=80=9D She already had her share of Cheddar Bay Biscuit battle =
stories, but the shrimp was something else: =E2=80=9CIt tops any customer s=
ervice experience I=E2=80=99ve had. Some people are just a different type o=
f stupid, and they all wander into Red Lobster.=E2=80=9D

What we discussed yesterday was the possibility =E2=80=94=C2=A0hinted at in=
 Red Lobster=E2=80=99s bankruptcy papers =E2=80=94=C2=A0that the endless sh=
rimp promotion was a way to funnel money from the failing Red Lobster to it=
s controlling shareholder Thai Union Group Pcl, which was also a big suppli=
er. The theory is roughly that, as Red Lobster slid into bankruptcy,=C2=A0T=
hai Union could not expect to get any value back=C2=A0as a shareholder; in =
fact, it valued its Red Lobster investment at zero by February.=C2=A0But it=
 could salvage a lot of value=C2=A0as a supplier, by selling Red Lobster a =
lot of shrimp. If Red Lobster paid full price for all those shrimp, that wo=
uld be profitable for Thai Union as a supplier. And if Red Lobster lost mon=
ey on every shrimp it bought, that would in theory be bad for Thai Union as=
 a shareholder,=C2=A0but if Thai Union=E2=80=99s shares were worthless anyw=
ay, it couldn=E2=80=99t get any worse. Instead, the money came out of the p=
ocket of Red Lobster=E2=80=99s creditors, who are now looking into whether =
there was anything amiss in the endless shrimp decision-making.
In some ways the dynamics are reminiscent of what we used to talk about as =
=E2=80=9Cthe MoviePass economy.=E2=80=9D There, the theory was that venture=
 capitalists wanted to fund businesses that were growing quickly and signin=
g up lots of enthusiastic customers, without particularly caring whether th=
ose businesses made money. Startups adapted to those incentives: It is easi=
er to grow quickly and impress your customers if you price your products wa=
y below cost, and so startups did. Sometimes this worked, and=C2=A0the star=
tups quickly built big networks of dedicated customers and could rationaliz=
e their economics, and sometimes it didn=E2=80=99t.
But the point was that, for a while, ordinary people=E2=80=99s lifestyles w=
ere subsidized by venture capitalists=E2=80=99 bets=C2=A0on growth. I once =
wrote, about competing=C2=A0SoftBank-backed food-delivery services:
In these situations it is instructive to remove a few layers of abstraction=
 and just think about what is actually happening here. At one end, the sove=
reign wealth fund of Saudi Arabia plows gigantic piles of money into SoftBa=
nk=E2=80=99s Vision Fund. At the other end, Mexico City=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=
legendary late-night snack spot El Moro=E2=80=9D can have someone =E2=80=9C=
deliver its churros and hot cocoa to takeout customers across the capital=
=E2=80=9D well below cost, subsidized by the Vision Fund. The King of Saudi=
 Arabia is sending hot chocolate to everyone in Mexico City. Here, have thi=
s nice hot chocolate, on the King of Saudi Arabia. Modern capitalism is alw=
ays so much stranger than you expect.
Same here but with shrimp. Here, too, arguably Thai Union was very interest=
ed in volume=C2=A0and indifferent to unit economics. Here arguably the trad=
e was that Thai Union was gifting shrimp to Red Lobster overeaters. Thai Un=
ion got paid well for the shrimp, and the customers underpaid for them, and=
 the whole transaction was subsidized =E2=80=94=C2=A0unwillingly =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0by Red Lobster=E2=80=99s creditors.=C2=A0

